y explain complicated concepts in simple and accessible ways. I feel like some of this genuinely makes me smarter (I hope), and some of it is just insight porn - they evoke a pleasant sensation in my brain of having learned something, and that gives me a little rush of dopamine, which keeps me reading."),mdx("p",null,"Their writing is ",mdx("strong",{parentName:"p"},"useful"),". I can see how Paul Graham's ideas can be useful in my life - I want to build a startup, and his writing clarifies the path towards it. Eliezer Yudkowsky teaches rationality, and that also feels useful, though less directly. Scott Alexander's ideas are less practically applicable to my life, but he still makes me feel like I'm learning stuff and getting smarter."),mdx("p",null,"They're ",mdx("strong",{parentName:"p"},"funny"),", they regularly use jokes or witty turns of phrase. I feel like this is one of the most important factors in engaging writing, but I still don't know how to actually do this, I don't have a formula for being funny on command."),mdx("p",null,"They write with ",mdx("strong",{parentName:"p"},"authority and conviction"),". I think this is something anyone should be able to do - avoid countless disclaimers, ",mdx("strong",{parentName:"p"},"have strong opinions"),", express them with conviction. It's much more interesting to read than the insecure authors constantly hedging their bets, and it's not at odds with being rational and open minded. Eliezer Yudkowsky, Ayn Rand, and Owen Cook are my favorite examples of speaking with conviction. they care deeply and passionately about something, see the world from a certain perspective, and unapologetically express it."),mdx("p",null,"A cool trick I have learned by listening to Harmontown (a podcast by Dan Harmon, the author of Community and Rick and Morty) is that it ",mdx("em",{parentName:"p"},"doesn't even matter")," which opinion you have. Often Dan will just ",mdx("strong",{parentName:"p"},"pick a strong stance")," and rant about something ridiculous, like some minor annoyance or a movie he disliked. This makes him almost automatically entertaining to listen to."),mdx("p",null,mdx("strong",{parentName:"p"},"Make abstract ideas concrete"),", by using specific real-life examples, vivid metaphors, interesting thoughts experiment. Almost any article or a podcast discussing abstract ideas becomes instantly more entertaining when the authors try to list specific examples of a general idea."),mdx("p",null,"Cause ",mdx("strong",{parentName:"p"},"emotional spikes"),' - both David Wong and Scott Alexander say things that feel like pushing a gas pedal on some sort of emotional issue. They will either directly talk about hot-button issues (like politics), or makes a vivid over the top parables and metaphors, or makes fun of bad/stupid people, which just grabs your attention. David Wong and Owen Cook often directly address their audience, calling out their weaknesses or insecurities, "yelling" at them to do better (in an inspiring way).'),mdx("p",null,"(imagine your loved one lying on the street bleeding out, and you urgently need a doctor) "),mdx("ul",null,mdx("li",{parentName:"ul"},`Concise, clear, eloquent. Basically what PG does, and what HPMOR does much more artistically.
